ExtraaLearn Lead-Conversion Project

Context

The online-education sector has accelerated dramaticallyespecially after COVID-19reaching an estimated $287 billion market value in 2023 with a CAGR of 10% (2018-2023). This rapid growth has intensified competition among EdTech startups, all vying to turn incoming leads (prospective learners who download a brochure, browse the website/app, or engage on social media) into paying customers. Understanding which leads are most likely to convert allows companies to focus follow-up efforts where they matter most.

Project Purpose

As part of a machine-learning course, I built and evaluated a predictive pipeline for ExtraaLearn (a hypothetical early-stage EdTech firm) using its historical lead data. The work showcased my ability to:

  • Model Conversion Probability develop and tune classification models that flag leads most likely to become paying customers.
  • Diagnose Key Drivers identify the features that have the greatest impact on conversion (e.g., first-touch channel, profile-completion level, website engagement).
  • Translate Insights into Action outline data-backed recommendations for marketing allocation and lead-nurture strategy.

(All analysis, code, and visuals were produced independently for academic credit and are now part of my public portfolio.)

Data Description

The data contains the different attributes of leads and their interaction details with ExtraaLearn. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary

  • ID: ID of the lead

  • age: Age of the lead

  • current_occupation: Current occupation of the lead. Values include 'Professional','Unemployed',and 'Student'

  • first_interaction: How did the lead first interacted with ExtraaLearn. Values include 'Website', 'Mobile App'

  • profile_completed: What percentage of profile has been filled by the lead on the website/mobile app. Values include Low - (0-50%), Medium - (50-75%), High (75-100%)

  • website_visits: How many times has a lead visited the website

  • time_spent_on_website: Total time spent on the website

  • page_views_per_visit: Average number of pages on the website viewed during the visits.

  • last_activity: Last interaction between the lead and ExtraaLearn.

    • Email Activity: Seeking for details about program through email, Representative shared information with lead like brochure of program , etc
    • Phone Activity: Had a Phone Conversation with representative, Had conversation over SMS with representative, etc
    • Website Activity: Interacted on live chat with representative, Updated profile on website, etc

  • print_media_type1: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Newspaper.

  • print_media_type2: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn in the Magazine.

  • digital_media: Flag indicating whether the lead had seen the ad of ExtraaLearn on the digital platforms.

  • educational_channels: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn in the education channels like online forums, discussion threads, educational websites, etc.

  • referral: Flag indicating whether the lead had heard about ExtraaLearn through reference.

  • status: Flag indicating whether the lead was converted to a paid customer or not.

Data Overview

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Exploratory data analysis is the first deep dive into a new dataset. It helps confirm data quality, reveal early patterns or outliers, and shape hypotheses before any modelling begins. The discussion below outlines the main investigative angles taken to turn raw lead records into business-ready insights.

Guiding questions for the analysis

  • How does a prospects current occupation influence the likelihood of moving through the funnel?
  • Does the initial touchpoint with ExtraaLearn (website, mobile app, social media, etc.) affect conversion probability?
  • Among the follow-up interaction modes (phone calls, e-mail, live chat, webinars), which ones correlate with the strongest outcomes?
  • Which acquisition channelsdigital ads, organic search, referrals, print media, and so ondeliver the best conversion efficiency?
  • When visitors supply more complete profile details, does that richer information translate into a higher chance of becoming a paying customer?

# --- Styling Constants ---
PLOT_BG_COLOR = '#F9F6F9' # Off-white background
# Define specific colors based on user request
COLOR_MULTI_CAT = '#0F1D4F'  # Dark Blue for plots with >= 3 categories
COLOR_BINARY_1 = '#0F1D4F'  # Dark Blue for the 'first'/more frequent category in binary plots
COLOR_BINARY_2 = '#7AC9ED'  # Light Blue for the 'second'/less frequent category in binary plots

AXIS_LINE_COLOR = COLOR_MULTI_CAT # Match axis line color to the primary dark blue
LIGHT_GRID_COLOR = 'rgba(211, 211, 211, 0.5)' # Faint light grey grid color
BAR_CORNER_RADIUS = 6 # Radius for rounded corners on bars
AXIS_LINE_WIDTH = 0.5 # Thinner axis line width
BAR_WIDTH = 0.5 # Make bars slightly narrower

# --- Function to plot numerical variables (Histogram and Box Plot - Unchanged from last version) ---
def plot_numerical(data, col_name):
    """
    Generates an interactive histogram and box plot for a numerical column,
    with updated axis colors and background.
    (Histogram corners remain square due to Plotly limitations).

    Args:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
        col_name (str): The name of the numerical column to plot.
    """
    if col_name not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return
    if not pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(data[col_name]):
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' is not numerical.")
        return

    print(f"--- Visualizing Numerical Column: {col_name} ---")

    # Create subplots: 1 row, 2 columns
    fig = make_subplots(rows=1, cols=2, subplot_titles=(f'Distribution (Histogram)', f'Spread (Box Plot)'))

    # Histogram
    hist_fig = px.histogram(data, x=col_name, marginal="rug", title=None)
    # Update histogram trace styling with the primary color
    hist_fig.update_traces(
        marker_color=COLOR_MULTI_CAT, # Use the main dark blue color
        opacity=0.8
        )
    for trace in hist_fig['data']:
        fig.add_trace(trace, row=1, col=1)

    # Box Plot
    box_fig = px.box(data, y=col_name, title=None, points='outliers')
     # Update box plot trace styling with the primary color
    box_fig.update_traces(marker_color=COLOR_MULTI_CAT) # Use the main dark blue color
    for trace in box_fig['data']:
        fig.add_trace(trace, row=1, col=2)

    # Update layout for the combined figure with clean styling
    fig.update_layout(
        title_text=f'Univariate Analysis: {col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}',
        title_x=0.5, # Center title
        showlegend=False,
        height=450,
        bargap=0.1,
        plot_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR, # Use new background color
        paper_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR, # Use new background color
        font=dict(color='black') # Ensure text is readable
    )
    # Update axes styling for both subplots - thinner lines matching COLOR_MULTI_CAT
    fig.update_xaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True, showgrid=False) # Ensure grid is off for x
    fig.update_yaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True, gridcolor=LIGHT_GRID_COLOR, showgrid=True) # Keep faint y-grid

    # Specific axis titles/ticks adjustments per subplot
    fig.update_xaxes(title_text=col_name.replace("_", " ").title(), row=1, col=1)
    fig.update_yaxes(title_text="Frequency", row=1, col=1)
    fig.update_xaxes(showticklabels=False, title_text="", row=1, col=2) # Hide x-axis ticks/title for box
    fig.update_yaxes(title_text=col_name.replace("_", " ").title(), row=1, col=2)

    fig.show()
    print("-" * 70)


# --- Function to plot categorical variables (Bar Plot - Updated Design) ---
def plot_categorical(data, col_name):
    """
    Generates an interactive bar plot for a categorical column,
    with conditional coloring (specific binary, single multi-cat),
    narrower/rounded bars, and bold white text inside.
    Axis lines are thin and match COLOR_MULTI_CAT.

    Args:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
        col_name (str): The name of the categorical column to plot.
    """
    if col_name not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return

    # Create a copy to avoid modifying original DataFrame
    local_data = data.copy()

    # Ensure column is treated as string for consistent mapping
    local_data[col_name] = local_data[col_name].astype(str)

    print(f"--- Visualizing Categorical Column: {col_name} ---")

    # Calculate value counts and sort
    counts = local_data[col_name].value_counts().reset_index()
    counts.columns = [col_name, 'count']
    counts = counts.sort_values(by='count', ascending=False) # Sort ensures consistent color assignment in binary case

    num_categories = counts.shape[0]

    # Create bar plot - Initially without explicit color arguments
    fig = px.bar(counts, x=col_name, y='count',
                 title=f'Univariate Analysis: Distribution of {col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}',
                 text='count' # Use the actual count column for text
                 )

    # --- Apply Styling and Conditional Coloring ---
    if num_categories >= 3:
        # Apply single color and other styles for multi-category plots
        fig.update_traces(
            marker=dict(
                color=COLOR_MULTI_CAT, # Single dark blue color
                cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS,
                line_width=0
            ),
            textposition='inside',
            insidetextanchor='middle',
            textfont=dict(color='white', size=12, family="Arial Black, sans-serif"),
            texttemplate='<b>%{text}</b>',
            width=BAR_WIDTH,
            hovertemplate=f'<b>{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>: %{{x}}<br><b>Count</b>: %{{y}}<extra></extra>'
        )
    elif num_categories == 2:
        # Apply specific colors and styles for binary plots
        # Assign colors based on the sorted order (more frequent gets dark blue)
        colors_binary = [COLOR_BINARY_1, COLOR_BINARY_2]
        fig.update_traces(
             marker=dict(
                 # Apply colors individually based on the sorted order
                 color=colors_binary,
                 cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS,
                 line_width=0
             ),
            textposition='inside',
            insidetextanchor='middle',
            textfont=dict(color='white', size=12, family="Arial Black, sans-serif"),
            texttemplate='<b>%{text}</b>',
            width=BAR_WIDTH,
            hovertemplate=f'<b>{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>: %{{x}}<br><b>Count</b>: %{{y}}<extra></extra>'
        )
    else: # Handle 0 or 1 category case
         fig.update_traces(
            marker=dict(
                color=COLOR_MULTI_CAT, # Default to dark blue
                cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS,
                line_width=0
            ),
            textposition='inside',
            insidetextanchor='middle',
            textfont=dict(color='white', size=12, family="Arial Black, sans-serif"),
            texttemplate='<b>%{text}</b>',
            width=BAR_WIDTH,
            hovertemplate=f'<b>{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>: %{{x}}<br><b>Count</b>: %{{y}}<extra></extra>'
        )
    # --- End Styling ---


    # Update layout for clean styling
    fig.update_layout(
        title_x=0.5, # Center title
        xaxis_title=col_name.replace("_", " ").title(),
        yaxis_title='Number of Leads',
        showlegend=False, # Legend is redundant
        height=450,
        plot_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        paper_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        font=dict(color='black'),
        yaxis_gridcolor=LIGHT_GRID_COLOR,
        yaxis_showgrid=True,
        xaxis_showgrid=False
    )
     # Update axes lines - thinner lines matching AXIS_LINE_COLOR
    fig.update_xaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)
    fig.update_yaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)

    fig.show()
    print("-" * 70)

print("Univariate visualization functions updated: plot_numerical() and plot_categorical()")

    • Model Algorithms: Some algorithms handle imbalance better than others, or have parameters (like class_weight='balanced') to address it.

Bivariate Analysis

In[70]:
# --- Consistent Styling Constants ---
PLOT_BG_COLOR = '#F9F6F9'     # Off-white background
COLOR_MULTI_CAT = '#0F1D4F'  # Dark Blue (Primary, used for multi-cat & highlights)
COLOR_BINARY_1 = '#0F1D4F'  # Dark Blue (For binary: Highest rate / First bar)
COLOR_BINARY_2 = '#7AC9ED'  # Light Blue (For binary: Lowest rate / Second bar)
AXIS_LINE_COLOR = COLOR_MULTI_CAT # Match axis line color to primary dark blue
LIGHT_GRID_COLOR = 'rgba(211, 211, 211, 0.5)' # Faint light grey grid color
BAR_CORNER_RADIUS = 6        # Radius for rounded corners on bars
AXIS_LINE_WIDTH = 0.5        # Thinner axis line width
BAR_WIDTH = 0.5              # Consistent bar width (optional, can adjust)

# --- Function to plot Categorical Predictor vs. Status (Target) - CORRECTED Style ---
def plot_categorical_vs_status(data, col_name, target='status'):
    """
    Generates an interactive bar chart showing the conversion rate (target=1)
    for each category of a categorical predictor column.
    Uses the updated color scheme (conditional binary/multi-category),
    rounded corners, and bold white text inside bars.

    Args:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
        col_name (str): The name of the categorical predictor column.
        target (str): The name of the target variable column (default: 'status').
    """
    # --- Input Validation ---
    if col_name not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return
    if target not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Target column '{target}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return

    # --- Data Preparation ---
    local_data = data.copy()
    if pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(local_data[col_name]):
        if local_data[col_name].nunique() > 20:
             print(f"Warning: Column '{col_name}' is numerical with many values. Bar plot might not be ideal.")
        local_data[col_name] = local_data[col_name].astype(str)

    original_dtype = local_data[target].dtype
    local_data[target] = pd.to_numeric(local_data[target], errors='coerce')
    rows_before = len(local_data)
    local_data.dropna(subset=[target], inplace=True)
    rows_after = len(local_data)
    if rows_before > rows_after:
        print(f"Warning: Dropped {rows_before - rows_after} rows where target '{target}' was not numeric (original dtype: {original_dtype}).")
    if local_data.empty:
        print(f"Error: No valid data remaining for column '{col_name}' after handling non-numeric target values.")
        return

    print(f"--- Bivariate Analysis: {col_name} vs. {target} ---")

    # --- Calculation ---
    conversion_rates = local_data.groupby(col_name)[target].mean().reset_index()
    conversion_rates = conversion_rates.sort_values(by=target, ascending=False) # Sort by rate

    # --- Determine number of categories for coloring ---
    num_categories = conversion_rates.shape[0] # Count categories *after* grouping

    # --- Plotting ---
    fig = px.bar(conversion_rates,
                 x=col_name,
                 y=target,
                 title=f'Conversion Rate by {col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}',
                 text=target
                )

    # --- Styling ---
    fig.update_layout(
        title_x=0.5,
        xaxis_title=col_name.replace("_", " ").title(),
        yaxis_title='Conversion Rate',
        yaxis_tickformat='.1%',
        plot_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        paper_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        xaxis_showgrid=False,
        yaxis_showgrid=True,
        yaxis_gridcolor=LIGHT_GRID_COLOR,
        showlegend=False,
        font=dict(color='black')
    )
    fig.update_xaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)
    fig.update_yaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)

    # --- Apply Conditional Coloring and Other Trace Styling ---
    common_trace_styling = dict(
        texttemplate='<b>%{text:.1%}</b>',
        textposition='inside',
        insidetextanchor='middle',
        textfont=dict(color='white', size=12, family="Arial Black, sans-serif"),
        width=BAR_WIDTH,
        hovertemplate=f'<b>{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>: %{{x}}<br><b>Conversion Rate</b>: %{{y:.1%}}<extra></extra>'
    )

    if num_categories == 2:
        # Apply specific colors for binary plots
        # Colors are applied based on the sorted order (highest rate gets first color)
        colors_binary = [COLOR_BINARY_1, COLOR_BINARY_2] # Dark Blue, Light Blue
        fig.update_traces(
             marker=dict(
                 color=colors_binary, # Apply list of colors
                 cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS,
                 line_width=0
             ),
            **common_trace_styling # Unpack common styles
        )
    else: # Handle 1 or >= 3 categories
         fig.update_traces(
            marker=dict(
                color=COLOR_MULTI_CAT, # Apply single dark blue color
                cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS,
                line_width=0
            ),
            **common_trace_styling # Unpack common styles
        )
    # --- End Styling ---

    fig.show()
    print("-" * 70)

# Keep the numerical function as it was correctly using the map
def plot_numerical_vs_status(data, col_name, target='status'):
    """
    Generates an interactive box plot showing the distribution of a numerical
    predictor for each category of the target variable. Uses the updated
    binary color scheme (dark blue for '1', light blue for '0').

    Args:
        data (pd.DataFrame): The DataFrame containing the data.
        col_name (str): The name of the numerical predictor column.
        target (str): The name of the target variable column (default: 'status').
    """
    # --- Input Validation ---
    if col_name not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return
    if target not in data.columns:
        print(f"Error: Target column '{target}' not found in DataFrame.")
        return
    if not pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(data[col_name]):
        print(f"Error: Column '{col_name}' is not numerical.")
        return

    # --- Data Preparation ---
    local_data = data.copy()
    if not pd.api.types.is_categorical_dtype(local_data[target]) and not pd.api.types.is_string_dtype(local_data[target]):
         local_data[target] = local_data[target].astype(str) # Convert target to string

    print(f"--- Bivariate Analysis: {col_name} vs. {target} ---")

    # --- Define Color Map using new constants ---
    color_map_binary = {
        '0': COLOR_BINARY_2, # Light Blue for '0'
        '1': COLOR_BINARY_1  # Dark Blue for '1'
    }

    # --- Plotting ---
    fig = px.box(local_data,
                 x=target,
                 y=col_name,
                 title=f'{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()} Distribution by Conversion Status',
                 points='outliers',
                 color=target,
                 color_discrete_map=color_map_binary
                )

    # --- Styling ---
    fig.update_layout(
        title_x=0.5,
        xaxis_title='Conversion Status (0: No, 1: Yes)',
        yaxis_title=col_name.replace("_", " ").title(),
        plot_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        paper_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
        xaxis_showgrid=False,
        yaxis_showgrid=True,
        yaxis_gridcolor=LIGHT_GRID_COLOR,
        showlegend=False,
        font=dict(color='black')
    )
    fig.update_xaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)
    fig.update_yaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)

    fig.update_traces(
        hovertemplate=f'<b>Status</b>: %{{x}}<br><b>{col_name.replace("_", " ").title()}</b>: %{{y}}<extra></extra>'
    )

    fig.show()
    print("-" * 70)

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) - Summary

I. Data Overview & Sanity Checks:

  • Dataset Size: 4612 leads (rows) and 14 features (columns) after dropping the 'ID'.
  • Data Quality:
    • No missing values were found in any column.
    • No duplicate rows were found.
    • Data types generally align with expectations (numerical for counts/time, object for categories).

II. Univariate Analysis (Individual Variable Insights):

  • Target Variable (status):
    • The dataset is imbalanced, with approximately 29.9% of leads converting (status=1) and 70.1% not converting (status=0). This imbalance needs consideration during modeling.
  • Numerical Variables:
    • age: Bimodal distribution, with peaks in the early 20s (students) and a larger peak in the 50s (professionals). Range: 18-63.
    • website_visits: Right-skewed. Most leads visit few times (median=3), but outliers visit up to 30 times. Some leads have 0 visits.
    • time_spent_on_website: Strongly right-skewed. Most leads spend little time (median=376s), but a few spend much longer (up to ~42 mins). Mean (724s) is much higher than the median.
    • page_views_per_visit: Right-skewed. Most leads view few pages per visit (median=2.8). Outliers view up to ~18 pages/visit on average.
  • Categorical Variables:
    • current_occupation: Dominated by 'Professional' (2616), followed by 'Unemployed' (1441), and 'Student' (555).
    • first_interaction: Fairly balanced between 'Website' (2542) and 'Mobile App' (2070).
    • profile_completed: Mostly 'High' (2264) or 'Medium' (2241), with very few 'Low' (107).
    • last_activity: 'Email Activity' (2278) is most common, followed by 'Phone Activity' (1234) and 'Website Activity' (1100).
    • Media/Channel Flags (print_media_type1, print_media_type2, digital_media, educational_channels, referral): All heavily skewed towards 'No'. Referrals are extremely rare (93 'Yes'). Educational channels had the highest 'Yes' count among these flags (705).

III. Bivariate Analysis (Relationships with Conversion Status):

  • Strong Predictors of Conversion:
    • referral: Leads from referrals have an exceptionally high conversion rate (~67.7%), though they are rare.
    • first_interaction: Website interaction leads convert at a much higher rate (~45.6%) than Mobile App leads (~10.5%).
    • profile_completed: Strong positive correlation. 'High' completion converts at ~41.8%, 'Medium' at ~18.9%, and 'Low' at ~7.5%.
    • time_spent_on_website: Very strong positive relationship. Converted leads spend significantly more time on the website than non-converted leads.
    • current_occupation: Professionals convert most (~35.5%), followed by Unemployed (~26.6%), and Students least (~11.7%).
  • Moderate/Weak Predictors:
    • last_activity: Website activity (~38.5%) leads convert more often than Email (~30.3%) or Phone (~21.3%).
    • page_views_per_visit: Positive association. Converted leads view more pages per visit on average.
    • website_visits: Positive association. Converted leads tend to have slightly more visits.
    • age: Very weak relationship. Distributions are largely similar, though converted leads might be slightly younger on average (median).
    • Media Flags (print_media_type1, print_media_type2, digital_media, educational_channels): Show very small differences in conversion rates between 'Yes' and 'No' groups. Their impact seems minimal, especially considering the low 'Yes' counts. Educational channels had a slightly lower conversion rate for the 'Yes' group.

IV. Key Takeaways for Modeling:

  • Variables related to user engagement (time_spent_on_website, page_views_per_visit, website_visits) and demonstrated intent/fit (profile_completed, current_occupation, first_interaction='Website', referral) appear to be the most promising predictors.
  • Demographics like age seem less predictive on their own.
  • Traditional advertising channels (print/digital flags) and educational channels seem less impactful on conversion likelihood compared to user behavior and profile data.
  • The class imbalance in status must be addressed.

This comprehensive EDA provides a solid foundation for the next steps, which typically involve data preprocessing (like encoding categorical variables, scaling numerical features) and then building and evaluating classification models.

Data Preprocessing

Now that we have explored the data and gained insights through EDA, the next crucial step is to prepare the data for machine learning models. This involves transforming the data into a suitable format and handling potential issues like outliers.

  • Duplicate Values: Our initial sanity checks confirmed that there are no duplicate rows in the dataset (df.duplicated().sum() returned 0).
  • Missing Values: Our initial check using df.info() and df.isnull().sum() showed that there are no missing values in any of the columns. This simplifies preprocessing significantly, as no imputation is needed.

The primary preprocessing steps we will focus on are:

  1. Outlier Detection and Treatment: We observed potential outliers in numerical features during EDA (especially in website interaction metrics). We need to formally identify and decide how to handle these.
  2. Encoding Categorical Features: Converting categorical variables (like current_occupation, profile_completed, etc.) into numerical representations suitable for ML algorithms.
  3. Feature Scaling: Scaling numerical features to a common range to ensure fair contribution to models sensitive to feature magnitudes.
  4. Train-Test Split: Separating the data into training and testing sets before applying certain preprocessing steps like scaling.

Let's begin by checking for outliers in the numerical columns.

In[85]:
# --- Outlier Detection using IQR ---

print("--- Checking for Outliers using the IQR Method ---")

# Select numerical columns to check (excluding the binary target 'status')
numerical_cols_to_check = ['age', 'website_visits', 'time_spent_on_website', 'page_views_per_visit']

# Check if columns exist
valid_cols = [col for col in numerical_cols_to_check if col in df.columns]
if not valid_cols:
    print("Error: None of the specified numerical columns found in the DataFrame.")
else:
    print(f"Checking columns: {valid_cols}\n")

    # Loop through each numerical column
    for col in valid_cols:
        print(f"Processing column: '{col}'")

        # Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)

        # Calculate the Interquartile Range (IQR)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1

        # Define the lower and upper bounds for outlier detection
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        print(f"  Q1: {Q1:.2f}, Q3: {Q3:.2f}, IQR: {IQR:.2f}")
        print(f"  Lower Bound (Q1 - 1.5*IQR): {lower_bound:.2f}")
        print(f"  Upper Bound (Q3 + 1.5*IQR): {upper_bound:.2f}")

        # Identify outliers
        outliers_lower = df[df[col] < lower_bound]
        outliers_upper = df[df[col] > upper_bound]
        outliers_total = pd.concat([outliers_lower, outliers_upper]) # Combine lower and upper outliers

        # Calculate the number and percentage of outliers
        num_outliers = len(outliers_total)
        total_values = len(df[col])
        percentage_outliers = (num_outliers / total_values) * 100 if total_values > 0 else 0

        print(f"  Number of outliers detected: {num_outliers}")
        print(f"  Percentage of outliers: {percentage_outliers:.2f}%\n")

print("-" * 70)
print("Outlier detection complete.")

  • Decision: We will keep these outliers in the dataset for now.

    • Tree-based models (e.g., Random Forest, Gradient Boosting), which are often effective for this type of problem, are generally robust to outliers.
    • We can revisit outlier treatment (e.g., capping or transformation) later if we decide to use models that are more sensitive to extreme values (e.g., Logistic Regression, SVM).

Machine learning algorithms, particularly those in scikit-learn, require numerical input. Therefore, we need to convert our categorical text features into numerical representations. We used two different methods based on the nature of the variables:

  • Ordinal Encoding (for profile_completed)

    • Why: The profile_completed feature has categories with a clear, inherent order ('Low' < 'Medium' < 'High').
    • How: We manually mapped these categories to integers (0, 1, 2) corresponding to their rank.
    • Benefit: This method preserves the ordinal relationship between the categories, allowing the model to potentially interpret 'High' (2) as being "more complete" than 'Low' (0).

  • One-Hot Encoding (for other categorical features)

    • Features: current_occupation, first_interaction, last_activity, print_media_type1, print_media_type2, digital_media, educational_channels, referral.
    • Why: These features are nominal their categories do not have a meaningful intrinsic order (e.g., 'Website' is not inherently "greater" or "less" than 'Mobile App'; 'Professional' is not ranked relative to 'Unemployed'). Applying simple numerical mapping (like 0, 1, 2) would impose an artificial and potentially misleading order.
    • How: We used pd.get_dummies(). This creates new binary (0 or 1) columns for each category within a feature. A '1' indicates the presence of that category for a given lead, and '0' indicates its absence.
    • Benefit: It represents categorical information numerically without implying any order between the categories.
    • drop_first=True: We used this option to drop one category from each original feature. This prevents perfect multicollinearity (redundancy) among the newly created dummy columns, which is important for some modeling techniques. The information from the dropped category is implicitly captured when all other dummy columns for that feature are 0.

This combination ensures that the nature of each categorical variable (ordinal vs. nominal) is appropriately represented in the numerical format required by the models.

Feature Scaling Decision

  • Standard Practice: Feature scaling (like Standardization or Normalization) is often applied to numerical features to bring them to a common scale. This is crucial for algorithms sensitive to feature magnitudes (e.g., Logistic Regression, SVM, KNN).
  • Decision: We will skip feature scaling for this analysis.
  • Rationale:
    • The primary models planned for this project are Decision Trees and Random Forests.
    • Tree-based models operate by finding optimal split points based on feature values. They are not sensitive to the absolute scale of the numerical features.
    • Therefore, scaling would not significantly impact the performance of these specific models and adds an unnecessary step to the current preprocessing pipeline.
    • If models sensitive to scale were to be used later, scaling could be introduced at that stage.

The data (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test) is now considered preprocessed and ready for model building using Decision Trees and Random Forests.

Building Classification Models

Now that the data is preprocessed, we will proceed to build classification models to predict lead conversion (status).

Model Evaluation Criterion

It's crucial to define how we measure success. A classification model can make two main types of errors in this context:

  1. False Negative (Type II Error): Predicting a lead will not convert (status=0), when in reality, they would have converted (status=1).
    • Business Impact: The company misses out on a potential paying customer because they didn't prioritize or nurture this lead appropriately. This represents lost revenue.
  2. False Positive (Type I Error): Predicting a lead will convert (status=1), when in reality, they will not convert (status=0).
    • Business Impact: The company might allocate sales/marketing resources (time, effort, cost) towards nurturing a lead who ultimately doesn't become a customer. This represents wasted resources.

Which Error is More Critical for ExtraaLearn?

  • For a startup like ExtraaLearn focused on growth, missing out on potential customers (False Negatives) is likely more costly than spending some resources on leads who don't convert (False Positives). Acquiring customers is essential for growth.
  • Therefore, we should prioritize minimizing False Negatives.

How to Minimize False Negatives?

  • The evaluation metric directly related to minimizing False Negatives is Recall (also known as Sensitivity or True Positive Rate). Recall measures the proportion of actual positive cases (converted leads) that the model correctly identified.
    • $Recall = \frac{True \ Positives}{True \ Positives + False \ Negatives}$
  • Our goal will be to build a model with high Recall, while still maintaining reasonable Precision (minimizing False Positives to avoid excessive resource waste) and overall Accuracy or F1-score. We will monitor multiple metrics, but prioritize Recall due to the business context.

We will now build our first model, a Decision Tree, and evaluate it using these criteria. We will also explore more complex models like Random Forest and tune hyperparameters to optimize performance, particularly focusing on maximizing Recall.

# Import necessary libraries for evaluation
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Function to print classification report and plot confusion matrix
def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    """
    Calculates and displays classification metrics and confusion matrix.

    Args:
        actual: The true target values (e.g., y_test).
        predicted: The values predicted by the model.
    """
    print("--- Model Evaluation Metrics ---")
    # Print the detailed classification report
    print("Classification Report:")
    try:
        # Ensure labels are consistent if needed, especially if only one class is predicted
        # Get unique labels from both actual and predicted to handle edge cases
        labels = sorted(list(set(actual) | set(predicted)))
        print(classification_report(actual, predicted, labels=labels, target_names=['Not Converted (0)', 'Converted (1)'])) # Added target_names
    except ValueError as e:
        print(f"Could not generate classification report: {e}")
        print("(This might happen if predictions contain only one class)")
        # Still try to print basic report if possible
        print(classification_report(actual, predicted))


    print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
    # Calculate the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)

    # Plot the confusion matrix using Seaborn heatmap
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4)) # Adjusted figure size slightly
    sns.heatmap(
        cm,
        annot=True, # Show the counts in the cells
        fmt=".0f",  # Format annotations as integers
        cmap='Blues', # Use a blue color map
        xticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted'], # Labels for x-axis (Predicted)
        yticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted']  # Labels for y-axis (Actual)
    )
    plt.ylabel('Actual Status')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Status')
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show() # Display the plot
    print("-" * 70)

print("Evaluation function 'metrics_score' defined.")

Next Step: Decision Tree Hyperparameter Tuning

  • What: Hyperparameters are settings of the model algorithm (like max_depth, min_samples_leaf) that are not learned from data but set beforehand. Tuning is the process of finding the best combination of these settings.
  • Why: The default settings (or our initial max_depth=5) are often not optimal. Tuning aims to improve the model's performance (especially our key metric, Recall) on unseen data by finding a better configuration, potentially balancing model complexity and generalization.
  • How: We will use techniques like Grid Search (GridSearchCV) with cross-validation on the training data (X_train, y_train) to systematically search for better hyperparameter values. We might also incorporate class_weight='balanced' to help address the class imbalance.
In[94]:
print("--- Decision Tree Hyperparameter Tuning using GridSearchCV ---")

# Check if training data exists
if 'X_train' not in globals() or 'y_train' not in globals() or X_train is None or y_train is None:
    print("Error: Training data (X_train, y_train) not found or not defined.")
else:
    try:
        # 1. Define the parameter grid to search
        param_grid = {
            'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'], # Splitting criterion
            'max_depth': [4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, None], # Maximum depth of the tree (None means nodes expand until pure or min_samples)
            'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10, 15],   # Minimum samples required to split an internal node
            'min_samples_leaf': [1, 3, 5, 7],      # Minimum samples required to be at a leaf node
            'class_weight': [None, 'balanced']  # Option to handle class imbalance
        }

        # 2. Create a base Decision Tree classifier instance
        dtree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

        # 3. Define the scoring metric - Prioritize Recall for the positive class (1)
        # pos_label=1 specifies that we want recall for the class labeled '1' (Converted)
        recall_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

        # 4. Instantiate GridSearchCV
        # - estimator: the model to tune
        # - param_grid: the hyperparameters to search
        # - cv=5: use 5-fold cross-validation
        # - scoring: the metric to optimize (Recall for class 1)
        # - n_jobs=-1: use all available CPU cores for faster search
        grid_search = GridSearchCV(
            estimator=dtree,
            param_grid=param_grid,
            scoring=recall_scorer,
            cv=5,
            n_jobs=-1,
            verbose=1 # Print updates during the search
        )

        # 5. Fit GridSearchCV on the training data
        print("Starting Grid Search CV... (This might take a few minutes)")
        grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
        print("Grid Search CV completed.")

        # 6. Get the best estimator and parameters
        best_dt_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
        print(f"\nBest Hyperparameters found:")
        print(grid_search.best_params_)

        # 7. Get the best score (Recall for class 1) achieved during cross-validation
        best_score = grid_search.best_score_
        print(f"\nBest Recall score (for class 1) during Cross-Validation: {best_score:.4f}")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during Grid Search CV: {e}")
        best_dt_model = None

print("-" * 70)

Decision Tree Pruning Rationale

  • Pruning Goal: Pruning aims to reduce tree complexity and prevent overfitting (where the model learns the training data too well, including noise, and fails to generalize to new data).
  • Pre-pruning vs. Post-pruning: Pruning can be done by limiting growth during training (pre-pruning) or by removing branches after training (post-pruning).
  • Hyperparameter Tuning as Pre-pruning: Our GridSearchCV process optimized pre-pruning hyperparameters like max_depth, min_samples_split, and min_samples_leaf. It found the values that resulted in the best performance (optimizing for Recall) during cross-validation.
  • Result: The resulting best_dt_model is already "pruned" in the sense that its complexity was controlled during tuning to maximize generalization.
  • Verification: The similar performance metrics observed on the training set and the test set for the best_dt_model confirm that it is not significantly overfitted.
  • Conclusion: Therefore, an additional post-pruning step is not required for this tuned Decision Tree model.

Next Model: Random Forest Classifier

  • Why Random Forest? While our tuned Decision Tree showed improved Recall, single decision trees can be prone to high variance small changes in the training data can lead to significantly different tree structures and predictions. They can also easily overfit if not carefully pruned/tuned.
  • Ensemble Power: Random Forest is an ensemble method that addresses these limitations. It builds multiple Decision Trees on different random subsets of the data (using techniques like bagging and random feature selection at each split).
  • How it Works: To make a prediction, Random Forest aggregates the predictions from all the individual trees (e.g., by majority vote for classification).
  • Benefits:
    • Reduced Overfitting: Averaging predictions from many trees generally leads to a model that generalizes better to unseen data than a single tree.
    • Increased Robustness: Less sensitive to noise or specific data points in the training set.
    • Often Higher Accuracy/Performance: Typically achieves better overall performance metrics.
  • Goal: We will build a Random Forest model to see if this ensemble approach can further improve our prediction performance, potentially achieving a good balance between Recall and Precision for lead conversion.

        # - class_weight='balanced': Attempts to adjust weights inversely proportional to class frequencies.
        #   This helps address the class imbalance directly within the model training.
        # - n_jobs=-1: Use all available CPU cores for training.
        rf_model_initial = RandomForestClassifier(

        rf_model_initial.fit(X_train, y_train)

        y_train_pred_rf_initial = rf_model_initial.predict(X_train)
        train_accuracy_rf_initial = accuracy_score(y_train, y_train_pred_rf_initial)
        print(f"\nQuick Check: Training Accuracy: {train_accuracy_rf_initial:.4f}")
        print("(This is accuracy on the data the model was trained on.)")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during Random Forest model training: {e}")
        rf_model_initial = None

Next Step: Random Forest Hyperparameter Tuning

  • Why Tune Random Forest? Our initial Random Forest model showed perfect performance on the training set but lower performance on the test set, indicating overfitting. The default parameters created trees that were too complex and essentially memorized the training data.
  • Goal: Hyperparameter tuning aims to find a better set of parameters (like the number of trees n_estimators, tree complexity controls max_depth, min_samples_leaf, etc.) that reduces overfitting and improves the model's ability to generalize to unseen data.
  • Optimization: We will tune the Random Forest specifically to optimize for Recall on the positive class (converted leads), similar to the Decision Tree tuning, while also considering the class_weight parameter to handle imbalance. This should help us find a more robust model that potentially balances Recall and Precision better than the tuned Decision Tree.
  • Method: We will again use GridSearchCV with cross-validation on the training data (X_train, y_train) to search for the optimal hyperparameter combination.
In[102]:
print("--- Random Forest Hyperparameter Tuning using GridSearchCV ---")

# Check if training data exists
if 'X_train' not in globals() or 'y_train' not in globals() or X_train is None or y_train is None:
    print("Error: Training data (X_train, y_train) not found or not defined.")
else:
    try:
        # 1. Define the parameter grid to search (Reduced grid for reasonable runtime)
        param_grid_rf = {
            'n_estimators': [100, 150],            # Number of trees
            'max_depth': [5, 7, 10, None],         # Max depth of each tree (None means full depth)
            'min_samples_split': [5, 10],          # Min samples to split a node
            'min_samples_leaf': [3, 5],            # Min samples at a leaf node
            'max_features': ['sqrt', 'log2'],      # Number of features to consider for best split
            'class_weight': ['balanced', None] # Handle imbalance
            # Add 'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'] if desired, but increases search space
        }

        # 2. Create a base Random Forest classifier instance
        # Set random_state for reproducibility, n_jobs for speed
        rf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42, n_jobs=-1)

        # 3. Define the scoring metric - Prioritize Recall for the positive class (1)
        recall_scorer = make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

        # 4. Instantiate GridSearchCV
        # - Using 3-fold CV instead of 5 to slightly reduce runtime
        grid_search_rf = GridSearchCV(
            estimator=rf,
            param_grid=param_grid_rf,
            scoring=recall_scorer,
            cv=3, # Reduced CV folds for speed
            n_jobs=-1,
            verbose=1 # Print updates during the search
        )

        # 5. Fit GridSearchCV on the training data
        print("Starting Grid Search CV for Random Forest... (This might take several minutes)")
        grid_search_rf.fit(X_train, y_train)
        print("Grid Search CV completed.")

        # 6. Get the best estimator and parameters
        best_rf_model = grid_search_rf.best_estimator_
        print(f"\nBest Hyperparameters found:")
        print(grid_search_rf.best_params_)

        # 7. Get the best score (Recall for class 1) achieved during cross-validation
        best_score_rf = grid_search_rf.best_score_
        print(f"\nBest Recall score (for class 1) during Cross-Validation: {best_score_rf:.4f}")

    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during Grid Search CV for Random Forest: {e}")
        best_rf_model = None

print("-" * 70)

Understanding Random Forest Models

  • Visualizing Individual Trees: Unlike a single Decision Tree, a Random Forest consists of many (often hundreds) of individual trees. Visualizing all of them is impractical, and looking at just one tree doesn't represent the combined decision-making of the whole ensemble.
  • Feature Importance: Therefore, instead of visualizing the trees directly, we analyze the model's feature importances. This tells us, on average, how much each feature contributed to reducing impurity (or improving the split criterion) across all the trees in the forest.
  • Goal: By visualizing feature importances, we can understand which factors the Random Forest model found most influential in predicting lead conversion, providing insights similar to, but often more robust than, those from a single Decision Tree.

We will now calculate and plot the feature importances for our tuned Random Forest model (best_rf_model).

In[105]:

AXIS_LINE_WIDTH = 0.5 # Thinner axis line width

print("--- Calculating and Visualizing Feature Importances for Tuned Random Forest ---")

# Check if the best model and training features exist
if 'best_rf_model' not in globals() or best_rf_model is None:
    print("Error: Tuned Random Forest model ('best_rf_model') not found. Please run GridSearchCV first.")
elif 'X_train' not in globals() or X_train is None:
    print("Error: Training data features (X_train) not found.")
else:
    try:
        # 1. Get feature importances from the tuned Random Forest model
        importances_rf = best_rf_model.feature_importances_
        feature_names_rf = X_train.columns.tolist() # Should be the same features as DT

        # 2. Create a DataFrame for easy sorting and plotting
        importance_rf_df = pd.DataFrame({
            'Feature': feature_names_rf,
            'Importance': importances_rf
        })

        # 3. Sort features by importance (descending)
        importance_rf_df = importance_rf_df.sort_values(by='Importance', ascending=False)

        # Filter out features with zero importance for a cleaner plot (optional)
        importance_rf_df = importance_rf_df[importance_rf_df['Importance'] > 0]

        # Limit to top N features if the list is too long (e.g., top 15)
        top_n = 15
        if len(importance_rf_df) > top_n:
             importance_rf_df = importance_rf_df.head(top_n)
             plot_title_rf = f"Top {top_n} Feature Importances (Tuned Random Forest)"
        else:
             plot_title_rf = "Feature Importances (Tuned Random Forest)"


        # 4. Create the horizontal bar chart using Plotly Express
        fig_rf = px.bar(importance_rf_df,
                        x='Importance', # Importance on the x-axis
                        y='Feature',    # Feature names on the y-axis
                        orientation='h', # Horizontal bars
                        title=plot_title_rf,
                        text='Importance' # Display importance value on bars
                       )

        # 5. Apply styling
        fig_rf.update_layout(
            title_x=0.5,
            plot_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
            paper_bgcolor=PLOT_BG_COLOR,
            font=dict(color='black'),
            yaxis={'categoryorder':'total ascending'}, # Order features by importance on y-axis
            xaxis_title='Importance Score (Mean Decrease in Impurity)', # More specific title
            yaxis_title='Feature',
            xaxis_gridcolor=LIGHT_GRID_COLOR, # Faint grid on value axis
            xaxis_showgrid=True,
            yaxis_showgrid=False, # No grid on category axis
            height=500 # Adjust height based on number of features
        )
        # Apply axis line styles
        fig_rf.update_xaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)
        fig_rf.update_yaxes(showline=True, linewidth=AXIS_LINE_WIDTH, linecolor=AXIS_LINE_COLOR, mirror=True)

        # Apply bar styling (color, rounded corners) and text format
        fig_rf.update_traces(
            marker=dict(color=PRIMARY_COLOR, cornerradius=BAR_CORNER_RADIUS, line_width=0),
            texttemplate='%{text:.3f}', # Format text to 3 decimal places
            textposition='outside', # Position text outside the bar for horizontal
            hovertemplate='<b>Feature</b>: %{y}<br><b>Importance</b>: %{x:.4f}<extra></extra>'
        )

        fig_rf.show()

    except AttributeError:
         print("Error: Could not get feature importances. Was the model trained?")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"An error occurred during feature importance visualization: {e}")

Model Comparison and Selection

Recap of Objectives:

As outlined in the project context, the primary goals for ExtraaLearn are to:

  • Build an ML model to identify which leads are more likely to convert to paid customers.
  • Find the factors driving the lead conversion process.
  • Create a profile of the leads who are likely to convert.

Evaluation Focus:

We established that minimizing False Negatives (missing potential customers) is crucial for ExtraaLearn's growth. Therefore, we prioritized maximizing Recall for the 'Converted' (1) class during model tuning, while also considering Precision and overall performance.

Model Comparison:

We have now trained and evaluated two candidate models on the test set:

  1. best_dt_model: Tuned Decision Tree
  2. best_rf_model: Tuned Random Forest

We will now compare their performance metrics side-by-side, focusing on Recall, Precision, F1-score, and Accuracy, to select the final model that best meets the business objectives.

Model Selection

  • Primary Goal: Our main objective was to maximize Recall for the 'Converted' class to minimize the number of missed potential customers (False Negatives).

  • Comparison: The Tuned Random Forest achieved a slightly higher Recall (88.4% vs. 86.9%) and resulted in fewer False Negatives (48 vs. 54) compared to the Tuned Decision Tree.

  • Trade-off: Both models have similar Precision (around 68-69%) and overall Accuracy/F1-scores. The Random Forest's slight edge in Recall comes with a negligible increase in False Positives (169 vs. 165).

  • Robustness: Random Forests are generally considered more robust and less prone to overfitting than single Decision Trees, even after tuning. The fact that its train and test scores were almost identical supports this.

  • Conclusion: Given its slightly superior performance on our key metric (Recall) and its inherent robustness as an ensemble model, the Tuned Random Forest (best_rf_model) is selected as the final model for predicting lead conversion for ExtraaLearn.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations

Profile of Leads Likely to Convert

Based on the Exploratory Data Analysis and the feature importances derived from the final Tuned Random Forest model, leads who are more likely to convert to paid customers for ExtraaLearn typically exhibit the following characteristics:

1. Initial Interaction Channel

  • They are significantly more likely to have had their first interaction via the Website rather than the Mobile App. The website channel yielded a much higher conversion rate (~46%) and was the top feature in the Random Forest model.

2. High Website Engagement

  • They spend a considerably longer total time on the website. This was the second most important feature and showed a strong positive correlation with conversion status in our analysis. While specific thresholds vary, higher time_spent_on_website is a strong positive indicator.

3. High Profile Completion

  • They tend to have completed their profile to a 'High' level. Profile completion was the third most important feature, and leads with 'High' completion had a substantially higher conversion rate (~42%) compared to 'Medium' or 'Low'.

4. Occupation

  • They are most likely to be 'Professionals'. This group had the highest conversion rate (~36%) among the occupation categories. Being a 'Student' was associated with lower conversion likelihood.

5. Recent Website Activity

  • While last_activity overall had moderate importance, leads whose last recorded interaction was Website Activity showed a higher conversion propensity (~39%) compared to those whose last activity was Email or Phone.

6. Age

  • While age had moderate importance in the model, the EDA didn't show a strong directional trend. However, the model likely uses age in combination with other features; the typical converting lead falls within the 18-63 range, with perhaps a slight tendency towards the established professional age group based on occupation findings.

7. If Referred

  • Although extremely rare in the dataset, leads who came via Referral have an exceptionally high chance of converting (~68%).

In essence, the ideal lead profile is an engaged professional who discovers ExtraaLearn through the website, invests time exploring the content, and demonstrates commitment by completing their profile.

Focusing sales and marketing efforts on leads matching this profile is likely to yield the highest return on investment.

Business Recommendations

Based on the analysis of lead data and the performance of the predictive models, here are actionable recommendations for ExtraaLearn to improve lead conversion rates and optimize resource allocation:

  • Prioritize Leads Based on Predictive Score & Key Features:

    • Implement the selected Tuned Random Forest model to score incoming leads based on their predicted probability of conversion.
    • Focus sales and nurturing efforts primarily on leads with high predicted scores.
    • Pay special attention to leads exhibiting the top predictive characteristics:
      • Initial interaction via the Website.
      • High time spent on the website.
      • 'High' profile completion status.
      • Occupation as 'Professional'.

  • Optimize Website Experience:

    • Given that first_interaction_Website and time_spent_on_website are the strongest predictors, ensure the website journey is seamless, engaging, and effectively captures lead information.
    • Analyze user paths on the website to understand what content or features correlate with longer engagement times and eventual conversion. Optimize these high-value paths.

  • Investigate Mobile App Channel:

    • The significantly lower conversion rate for leads originating from the Mobile App warrants investigation. Analyze the app's user experience, the type of leads it attracts, and the calls-to-action within the app. Is it serving a different purpose (e.g., information gathering) than the website? Consider A/B testing improvements.

  • Encourage Profile Completion:

    • Since 'High' profile completion strongly correlates with conversion, incentivize or simplify the process for leads to complete their profiles more fully. This provides valuable data and signals higher lead commitment.

  • Tailor Outreach by Occupation:

    • Recognize that 'Professionals' are the highest converting group. Tailor marketing messages and program offerings to resonate with their upskilling/reskilling needs.
    • Develop specific strategies for the 'Unemployed' segment, potentially highlighting career transition benefits.
    • Re-evaluate the approach for 'Students', as they have the lowest conversion rate; perhaps different programs or pricing models are needed for this group.

  • Leverage Referrals (If Scalable):

    • Although rare currently, referred leads convert at an exceptionally high rate. Explore the feasibility of implementing or enhancing a referral program to encourage existing customers or partners to refer new leads. Even a small increase in high-quality referred leads could be valuable.

  • Review Advertising & Channel Strategy:

    • The data suggests that leads attributed to specific print media, digital media, or educational channels (via the flags) do not convert at significantly higher rates than average.
    • Review the ROI of these specific flagged channels. While they might contribute to overall brand awareness, focus lead generation efforts on channels demonstrably bringing in high-engagement leads (like the Website).

  • Refine Lead Nurturing Based on Activity:

    • Leads whose last activity was on the website show higher conversion potential. Ensure follow-up mechanisms are in place to quickly engage these recently active leads.
    • Analyze the effectiveness of phone outreach, as it had the lowest conversion rate among last activities in this dataset. Ensure calls are focused and add value, potentially prioritizing calls for higher-scoring leads.

  • Continuous Model Monitoring & Improvement:

    • Periodically retrain the model with new data to ensure it remains accurate as market conditions or lead behaviors change.
    • Continuously monitor the model's performance, paying attention to the trade-off between Recall and Precision based on evolving business priorities.
    • Consider collecting additional data points that might further improve prediction accuracy (e.g., specific course interest, previous education level).
